Methodology

The SmartSpend budget calculator was developed as a budgeting tool that helps students allocate 
their allowance across different spending categories. The program was written in Python and follows 
a step-by-step interactive process where the user inputs their financial information and receives 
feedback based on validation checks.

The program starts by displaying a welcome message about SmartSpend as a budget calculator designed 
for students. 

The feature implemented is allowance input validation. The program asks the user to input their total 
allowance using the input() function. Since users may accidentally input invalid values such as letters
or symbols, the program uses a try and except block to catch errors that occur when converting the input
into a numerical value using float(). If an invalid input is detected, the program displays an error message
and asks the user to try again.

A while True loop ensures that the program continues prompting the user until a valid allowance is entered,
additionally, the program checks whether the entered allowance is greater than zero. If the user enters zero 
or a negative number, the program informs the user that the allowance must be greater than zero and repeats 
the input process. This prevents unrealistic or incorrect budget calculations.

After receiving a valid allowance value, the program proceeds to the budget allocation stage. In this section, 
the user assigns percentages of their allowance to five categories: School, Necessities, Wants, Savings, and Food. 
These categories were chosen because they represent common spending areas for students.

Each percentage is collected individually and converted to a floating-point number. Similar to the allowance input,
the program uses error handling to prevent invalid inputs such as letters or symbols. The program also checks if any
of the percentages are negative values. If negative numbers are detected, the program displays an error message and 
asks the user to input the values again.

Once all percentages are entered, the program performs a validation check to determine whether the sum of the 
percentages equals exactly 100%. This ensures that the user distributes their entire allowance without exceeding
or missing any portion of the budget. If the total does not equal 100%, the program notifies the user and asks 
them to re-enter the percentages.

This validation process ensures that the budgeting system remains consistent and logically correct. When the percentages 
successfully add up to 100%, the program confirms the correct allocation and prints a message thanking the user for using
SmartSpend.





